minated by three issues: mercantilism's promise that civilization and wealth would be transmitted from London to the provinces; the debate over the extent of metropolitan prerogatives in law and commerce when they obtruded upon provincial rights and interests; and the argument that Britain's imperium pelagi was an ethical empire, because it depended upon the morality of trade, while the empires of Spain and France were immoral empires because they were grounded upon conquest. In discussing these issues, Shields provides a virtual anthology of poems long lost to students of American literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAmerican poetryyColonial period, ca. 1600-1775xHistory and criticism. 0aColonies in literature. 0aCommerce in literature. 0aImperialism in literature. 0aPolitical poetry, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  apoetry, poems, literature, literary, commerce, political, politics, british america, early american culture, cultural studies, glorious revolution, king george war, empire, colonies, colonial, canada, west indies, mercantilism, civilization, wealth, london, law, ethics, morality, morals, colonialism, mercantile, liberty, monarchy, imperialism, imperialist, united states, 18th century.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999z978311066785140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226752990423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226752990/original  a978-3-11-066785-1  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999c1990d1999  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles